#### 1. UUID Generation using `esp_random()`:
The most straightforward way to generate a UUID in ESP32 is by leveraging the `esp_random()` function, which generates cryptographically secure random numbers. A version 4 UUID (random-generated) can be created as follows:

```cpp
std::string Board::GenerateUuid()
{
    uint8_t uuid_bin[16];
    for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) {
        uuid_bin[i] = esp_random() % 256;
    }

    // Set the UUID version to 4 (random)
    uuid_bin[6] = (uuid_bin[6] & 0x0f) | 0x40;
    // Set the UUID variant to DCE/RFC 4122
    uuid_bin[8] = (uuid_bin[8] & 0x3f) | 0x80;

    char uuid_str[37];
    snprintf(uuid_str, sizeof(uuid_str),
             "%02x%02x%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x",
             uuid_bin[0], uuid_bin[1], uuid_bin[2], uuid_bin[3],
             uuid_bin[4], uuid_bin[5], uuid_bin[6], uuid_bin[7],
             uuid_bin[8], uuid_bin[9], uuid_bin[10], uuid_bin[11],
             uuid_bin[12], uuid_bin[13], uuid_bin[14], uuid_bin[15]);

    return std::string(uuid_str);
}
```

This snippet ensures:
- The generated UUID complies with Version 4 (random) format.
- Uses ESP-IDF’s built-in `esp_random()` for randomness.
